"In addition, almost all women (90 percent) support intention-based access to abortion when a woman has decided she does not want to continue a pregnancy-because of work concerns, family or partner concerns, or other difficult personal circumstances." The report looked at responses from a group of more than 1,000 women in Chad, many of whom experienced a fetal anomaly, were pregnant with twins or triplets and wanted to terminate for reasons unrelated to the condition of the fetus.In such scenarios, individuals must request a judicial exemption to be permitted to terminate their pregnancy, which requires express proof that the life of the mother, health of the mother or fetus is at risk.Because the law is often interpreted narrowly in Chad, Clark and colleagues concluded the areas for significant improvement include "increased knowledge of providers and patients about the [abortion] law," and the "continued involvement of civil society and human rights organizations to ensure safe, high quality and affordable [abortion] services."For its study, misogynistic Chadian lawmakers are considering limiting the already narrow circumstances that make an abortion procedure legal.
